## Opening Thought
Unity is rarely simple, even inside a single party. Each state carries its own priorities, history, and economics. What unites Democrats in California may divide Democrats in Georgia, and what motivates Republicans in Texas may sound foreign to Republicans in Massachusetts. Before legislation ever gets started in Washington, compromise begins at home, where state platforms translate local needs into state party doctrine. When that first tier of compromise breaks down, the second tier, national agreement, never stands a chance.  

---

## Research Framing
I wondered what the state-level parties listed as their priorities, something that would frame the field of discussion going forward. At first, I believed both parties in states in the East would have more in common than the parties in the West. To explore this theory, I sampled two states from five different areas in the United States. The results were interesting.  

---

